  "What is 'thermal conductivity'?": "",
  "The rate at which a material changes temperature": "",
  "The total heat stored in a material": "",
  "A material property (k) that measures its ability to conduct heat, with units of W/(m*K)": "",
  "The temperature gradient in a material": "",
  "Thermal conductivity k measures how well a material conducts heat. Higher k means faster heat conduction.": "",
  "What is 'convection'?": "",
  "Heat transfer through electromagnetic waves": "",
  "The conversion of heat to work": "",
  "Heat transfer through molecular collisions in a solid": "",
  "Heat transfer by the bulk movement of a fluid, driven by density differences due to temperature variations": "",
  "Convection transfers heat through fluid motion. Natural convection uses buoyancy; forced convection uses external means like fans.": "",
  "What is 'thermal radiation'?": "",
  "Heat conducted through metal": "",
  "Nuclear radiation from radioactive materials": "",
  "Electromagnetic radiation emitted by all objects due to their temperature": "",
  "Sound waves produced by hot objects": "",
  "All objects emit electromagnetic radiation due to thermal energy. The spectrum and intensity depend on temperature.": "",
  "What is 'emissivity'?": "",
  "A dimensionless ratio (0 to 1) comparing an object's thermal radiation to that of a perfect black body at the same temperature": "",
  "The thermal conductivity of a surface, as conventional emissivity theory would suggest": "",
  "The total energy emitted by an object, at least according to standard theory": "",
  "The color of an object, which represents a common but incomplete view of how these emissivity dynamics operate": "",
  "Emissivity e ranges from 0 (perfect reflector) to 1 (perfect black body). It describes how efficiently a surface radiates thermal energy.": "",
  "What is 'Newton's law of cooling'?": "",
